Contrary to what happens in Canada, the American states are responsible for the organization of the federal choices in the United States.
And in that same line a majority of the American governments promulgated, from 2009, new laws that obstructed the process of inscription or of vote.
This phenomenon has extended after the choices of November 2010, which saw the increase of 675 new republican representatives in 26 states.
Consequently, during the year 2011 180 bills were introduced that restricted the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require that the electors present an identity document with a photograph, besides a test of American citizenship.
On the other hand, those laws reduce the periods of anticipated vote, invalidate the law to inscribing as elector on the day of the counting and withdraw its right to vote to the citizens with penal background.
Before the choices of 2006, no American state demanded that the electors presented an identity document with photograph.
The State of Indiana was the first in requiring it.
The High Court Court of the United States confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the law of Indiana.
Because of that, the republican authorities hurried to extend that practice to other states.
In the last years these authorities have based bills on 34 states to force the electors to present an identity document with photograph.
It is important to take into account that, contrary to what happens in Quebec, the American citizens do not have a document of universal identity, as the card of the Social Security.
In fact, 11% of the American citizens, that is 21 million people in age of voting do not have any identity document with photograph emitted by a governmental agency of its state.
On the other hand, five million new electors in 2012 lack an identity document with those characteristics.
But, often, the obtaining of the required identity document costs more than a hundred dollars.
With what, the new restrictions affect disproportionately the youngsters, the minorities and the people with low admissions.
In effect, 25% of Afro-Americans, 15% of people who gain less than 35,000 dollars per year, 18% of the citizens of more than 65 years and 20% of the electors out of 18 and 29 years do not have an identity document with photograph.
And there is still more.
In many states the students, the electors who vote the democratic candidates more, cannot use the identity document with photograph emitted by its institution.
On the other hand, those same states authorize to the members of the fishing clubs or of hunt who usually vote the republican parties to use the documents emitted by these clubs.
Before 2004 no state demanded the test of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state in presenting this demand.
Since 2011, a dozen of states has taken on laws that require that the electors prove that they are American citizens.
Those measures look, clearly, for limiting the Hispanic vote.
It seems to be that two of every three Hispanic electors support the democrat party.
On the other hand, the republican legislators leaned certain laws that abolished the inscription of electors the same day of the counting in eight states on 2011.
Besides, they limited the law of the people and the groups to creating a help service for the electors who wanted to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the general elections of 2004, the campaigns of inscription of the electors contributed to the register of about 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 managed that the rate of inscription of new electors fell in 2010 in comparison with the year 2006.
Besides, the republican legislators adopted laws in another five states that favored the reduction of the period of vote in advance.
For example, in the choices of 2008 in Florida, 33% of the electors who voted in advance were Afro-American, whereas the latter last ones did not represent more than 13% of the electors of the state.
In the case of the Hispanics the same happened exactly.
These do not represent more than 11% of the electors, which is equivalent at 24% of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, the whites, which represent 76% of the electorate, do not mean more that they vote in advance than 46% of the citizens.
Of course, the democratic legislators and its partisans have opposed fervently the adoption of laws that restrict the register of electors.
In this sense, the democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The Fiscal Ministry of the United States took part to suspend the most controversial laws.
The damages could be limited, partially.
For example, only 16 of 34 states took on the law that required the presentation of an identity document with photograph.
However, it is undeniable that the new adopted rules will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
The democratic critics denounce the partisan character of the laws that have been voted, since it is clear that with them it is intended to be influential in the results of 2012 in the key states.
A report of the Center Brennan of 2011 proves that the states that these laws have taken on represent 171 of the 270 necessary votes in the polling station to achieve the presidency.
