Poland and the cosmos.
In the meeting of ministers of the countries of the Space Agency European last week celebrated was accepted to Poland as twelfth member of the THAT ONE. It is the second member country of the THAT ONE of the old block of Eastern Europe, after the Czech Republic, which was converted in full member on 12 of November 2008).
Poland initiated an intense collaboration with the THAT ONE in the year 1994 and during the posterior years it took part in the commission of projects of the agency.
However, the path of Poland towards the cosmos started a lot before.
The Polish enthusiasts already dedicated themselves to the flights to the space before the Second World War, although its work was not always understood.
Memory, for example, the conference of A. Šternfeld in the astronomical observatory of Warsaw in the one that, on 6 of December 1933, presented its ideas on the pioneer study "Introduction to the cosmonautics".
The ideas about the young engineer (1905 born) left to the indifferent assistants and, years afterwards, Šternfeld remembered that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one that had shown interest in its work.
In the year 1934 Šternfeld obtained the prize Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch in France for its "Introduction to the cosmonautics".
The doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned previously, converted later in a great instigator of the astronomy and of the cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski converted in a promoter of the cosmonautics, it was known in all the world and its contribution to the science was seen recompensed when its name was put at one of the craters of the hidden face of the moon.
A track car that was going to be provided with an engine of rockets was already in the year 1925 built in Poland.
Regrettably, it is not known who was the author of the proposal and the dewaists of the project are not known either.
It is not clear if the rocket was going to be used for the starter of the track car or for its braking.
The information on this track car is limited to the collection in the press of the period.
From the year 1933 the Polish artillery started to be dedicated to the missiles.
The research was financed by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it is done evident that the research arrived to the stadium of the practical tests.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the research was interrupted.
In the year 1937 the prototype of a missile of photoelectric fighter designed by the engineer Rohoziński appeared in the technical press and the following year the study "Rakieta" was published "- torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza", of the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were destined for the military use of the engines for missiles.
Little before the war, the temporary scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was in charge of all the projects of techniques of missiles for military use and coordinated all the works.
The committee was founded in 1937, but it after two years of activity, was seen interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies dedicated to the cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the edition of November of 1954 of the magazine Problemy is done reference for the first time to the society with four very lengthy articles dedicated themselves to the astronautics.
In one of them, of the prof. M. Subotowicze, the creation of a society that would dedicate itself to the cosmonautics was suggested.
In that period projects of artificial satellites had already been started off and it was obvious that the cosmic research was a discipline with perspectives of future.
From the beginning of 1956 the Polish Society of Astronautics (PTA) aspired to be part of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in fall of that same year the PTA converted in full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), passed to to be the vice-president of the Federation International of Astronautics.
It held this charge up to its death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA shared significant way in the development of the rocket probe RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was a success and converted in the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was finished in 1957 and was launched by first time on the 10th of October 1958.
The rocket had an apogee of 1,800 meters, about 80 linear cm and did not arrive at the 5 weighty kg.
Later, the version RM finished being built-1 A and in summer of 1959 the air tests of the RM-2 rockets of two stages began in the desert of Błędów.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket in development was going to be the target of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was going to have an apogee of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the height wind.
However, in 1962 the works were suspended.
